ge may be fetishized or domesticated, marked for assimilation, or turned into an object of fear. A fresh look at ways to cultivate ethical responsibility for global issues, Staging Strangers imagines a role for theatre in creating a more tolerant, caring, and cooperative world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicity in the theater. 0aIntercultural communication in the performing artszCanada. 0aMulticulturalism in the theaterzCanada. 0aRace in the theaterzCanada. 0aTheater and globalizationzCanada. 0aTheater and internationalismzCanada. 0aTheater and societyzCanada. 0aTheaterzCanadaxHistoryy21st century. 0aTheaterzCanada. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354953140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773549531423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773549531/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles